WEBVTT

1
00:00:50.489 --> 00:00:51.569
Go!

2
00:00:55.399 --> 00:00:56.439
Go!

3
00:01:00.699 --> 00:01:01.829
What's that?

4
00:01:02.649 --> 00:01:03.739
It's a man!

5
00:01:04.909 --> 00:01:06.819
- What? Is he dead?
- No, sir.


6
00:01:07.039 --> 00:01:08.729
He's writing!

7
00:01:08.949 --> 00:01:09.949
Repeat!

8
00:01:10.649 --> 00:01:11.649
He's writing, sir

9
00:01:11.779 --> 00:01:14.599
he's writing in a notebook!

10
00:01:14.859 --> 00:01:17.899
That man was not mad.
He was working


11
00:01:18.029 --> 00:01:21.859
with shrapnel whistling round him
because he couldn't wait.


12
00:01:22.069 --> 00:01:24.369
The contents of that notebook
were too important


13
00:01:24.439 --> 00:01:26.049
to write it down later.

14
00:01:26.219 --> 00:01:28.959
He had to do it
when his mind dictated,


15
00:01:29.129 --> 00:01:31.699
he couldn't put it off
a single second.


16
00:01:32.909 --> 00:01:36.299
What was so important that
he would risk his life for it?


17
00:01:36.819 --> 00:01:39.819
What was he writing that
stopped him from standing up


18
00:01:39.989 --> 00:01:41.869
and running, like any other man
would have done?


19
00:01:46.379 --> 00:01:49.679
The "tractatus
logico-philosophicus",


20
00:01:52.119 --> 00:01:55.849
the most influential philosophical
work of the twentieth century.


21
00:01:56.369 --> 00:01:59.419
That soldier was called
Ludwig wittgenstein,


22
00:01:59.589 --> 00:02:02.239
the man who set the limits
on our thoughts.


23
00:02:03.199 --> 00:02:05.928
The enigma that
he tried to decipher


24
00:02:06.578 --> 00:02:07.888
was the following:

25
00:02:12.058 --> 00:02:14.578
Can we know the truth?

26
00:02:17.488 --> 00:02:19.358
All the great thinkers
throughout history


27
00:02:19.488 --> 00:02:21.268
have sought a single certainty,

28
00:02:21.438 --> 00:02:23.348
something which
no one can refute,


29
00:02:23.528 --> 00:02:25.998
like "two and two make four".

30
00:02:27.138 --> 00:02:29.048
In order to find that truth,

31
00:02:29.218 --> 00:02:31.128
wittgenstein used, in fact,

32
00:02:31.308 --> 00:02:35.648
mathematical logic. What better
means of obtaining a certainty


33
00:02:35.778 --> 00:02:39.338
than an immutable language,
free from the passions of men?


34
00:02:40.818 --> 00:02:44.858
He advanced slowly,
using equation after equation,


35
00:02:44.988 --> 00:02:47.768
with impeccable method,
until he reached


36
00:02:47.948 --> 00:02:49.768
a terrifying conclusion.

37
00:02:51.638 --> 00:02:54.198
There is no such truth

38
00:02:54.458 --> 00:02:56.768
outside of mathematics.

39
00:02:57.198 --> 00:02:58.938
There is no way of finding

40
00:02:59.108 --> 00:03:01.458
a single absolute truth,

41
00:03:01.628 --> 00:03:03.498
an irrefutable argument

42
00:03:03.668 --> 00:03:07.018
which might help answer
the questions of mankind.


43
00:03:08.628 --> 00:03:11.668
Philosophy, therefore, is dead.

44
00:03:13.448 --> 00:03:16.188
Because "whereof we cannot speak,

45
00:03:18.178 --> 00:03:20.788
thereof we must be silent."

46
00:04:44.907 --> 00:04:46.507
Don't touch that, please.

47
00:04:47.027 --> 00:04:48.547
This is an enigma machine!

48
00:04:48.727 --> 00:04:52.197
Just a copy. The original's in
the imperial war museum in London.


49
00:04:52.987 --> 00:04:55.287
Sorry to sneak in like that...
The door was open.


50
00:04:55.457 --> 00:04:59.157
Of course it was open. You surely
didn't expect me to get up


51
00:04:59.327 --> 00:05:00.887
and let you in
on these legs, did you?


52
00:05:01.327 --> 00:05:02.327
I'm...

53
00:05:02.537 --> 00:05:08.317
Martin, our new overseas
student lodger, I presume.


54
00:05:09.537 --> 00:05:11.887
- This man in the photo with you...
- Yes.


55
00:05:12.057 --> 00:05:14.147
That's turing, Alan turing,

56
00:05:14.747 --> 00:05:17.137
the man who deciphered
the enigma code.


57
00:05:17.317 --> 00:05:20.437
Thanks to him, we won the war.

58
00:05:20.567 --> 00:05:22.697
Poor man died
such a strange death...


59
00:05:23.617 --> 00:05:26.657
A poisoned apple, like snow white.

60
00:05:27.737 --> 00:05:29.307
And the one on the left?

61
00:05:29.477 --> 00:05:31.477
My husband, Harry.

62
00:05:31.647 --> 00:05:34.777
Harry eagleton. He developed the
concept of fractional dimensions...


63
00:05:34.957 --> 00:05:38.127
He deserved a bloody nobel prize,
but he hated sucking up


64
00:05:38.297 --> 00:05:40.817
to politicians.
Politicians or anybody.


65
00:05:40.947 --> 00:05:42.297
He never had many friends.

66
00:05:43.337 --> 00:05:45.637
He had one at least.
Arthur seldom.


67
00:05:45.817 --> 00:05:47.987
Poor boy. He spent day

68
00:05:48.117 --> 00:05:50.937
after day in the house,
tidying Harry's papers.


69
00:05:51.067 --> 00:05:54.767
He'd go without lunch or dinner,
going over the equations.


70
00:05:55.417 --> 00:05:59.237
Eagleton tutored his doctoral thesis
on the logical series. In 1960,


71
00:05:59.417 --> 00:06:02.407
- wasn't it?
- I see you've done your homework.


72
00:06:02.757 --> 00:06:05.187
I know everything there is
to know about Arthur seldom.


73
00:06:05.327 --> 00:06:07.627
In fact, Mrs. eagleton,
it's because of him that I'm here.


74
00:06:07.797 --> 00:06:09.367
In Oxford, I mean.

75
00:06:10.186 --> 00:06:13.146
I know what you mean.
Seldom is... unique.


76
00:06:14.096 --> 00:06:15.876
Every prize,
every acknowledgement


77
00:06:16.056 --> 00:06:20.446
he's received over the years
has been a real joy for me.


78
00:06:21.266 --> 00:06:23.486
Careful, mother, or
your secret will be discovered.


79
00:06:23.616 --> 00:06:24.696
What secret?

80
00:06:24.876 --> 00:06:26.566
After daddy died,
you tried to marry him.


81
00:06:26.696 --> 00:06:29.696
How dare you!
That's not true.


82
00:06:29.826 --> 00:06:31.316
He's always been
like a brother to me.


83
00:06:31.346 --> 00:06:33.296
Only because there was no chance
of him being anything else.


84
00:06:33.476 --> 00:06:34.566
Beth!

85
00:06:35.516 --> 00:06:37.516
There's no doubt
professor seldom is a genius,


86
00:06:37.686 --> 00:06:39.866
but there's one area
he's no different from other men.


87
00:06:40.906 --> 00:06:42.466
He likes young girls.

88
00:06:42.646 --> 00:06:46.376
Beth, darling, couldn't you stop
being so spiteful just for a second?


89
00:06:46.556 --> 00:06:47.726
Sorry, mother.

90
00:06:47.946 --> 00:06:50.726
Take no notice of us.
We're like two bitter old spinsters.


91
00:06:51.856 --> 00:06:55.156
Thank you, mother, for tarring me
with the same brush.


92
00:06:56.236 --> 00:06:57.256
I'm sorry,

93
00:06:57.286 --> 00:06:58.456
you are?

94
00:06:58.756 --> 00:07:01.366
I sent a fax a few weeks ago,
about renting a room.


95
00:07:01.546 --> 00:07:03.276
Ah, our overseas student.

96
00:07:03.406 --> 00:07:05.146
Why don't you
show him to his room?


97
00:07:08.056 --> 00:07:09.626
If I'd known,
I'd have rented a tux.


98
00:07:10.096 --> 00:07:11.356
You look stunning.

99
00:07:11.576 --> 00:07:13.876
My daughter has
a concert tonight. That's all.


100
00:07:14.536 --> 00:07:15.316
A concert?

101
00:07:15.486 --> 00:07:17.836
I play the cello
in the sheldonian.


102
00:07:18.096 --> 00:07:20.226
- It's the local amateur orchestra.
- Yes.


103
00:07:20.486 --> 00:07:22.746
We're not quite
the London symphony.


104
00:07:22.916 --> 00:07:24.086
I... I love the cello.

105
00:07:24.266 --> 00:07:27.606
Me too. Maybe it's because
it's all I get to cuddle


106
00:07:27.736 --> 00:07:28.866
- these days.
- Beth.


107
00:07:29.046 --> 00:07:30.476
Please.
You'll scare the young man.


108
00:07:30.646 --> 00:07:31.646
Mother.

109
00:07:31.866 --> 00:07:33.956
My daughter's suitors
tend not to be


110
00:07:34.126 --> 00:07:35.516
around very long.

111
00:07:35.696 --> 00:07:36.896
Difficult character, you know.

112
00:07:37.476 --> 00:07:40.426
Having an old lady hovering in the
doorway doesn't exactly help either.


113
00:07:40.596 --> 00:07:43.036
Are you calling me a busybody?

114
00:07:43.206 --> 00:07:45.636
No, mother. You just want
to protect me, don't you?


115
00:07:46.166 --> 00:07:47.336
Of course.

116
00:07:47.596 --> 00:07:48.816
My mother has this theory

117
00:07:48.986 --> 00:07:51.156
that unless a man lived
through the second world war


118
00:07:51.336 --> 00:07:52.856
he's not to be trusted.

119
00:07:53.026 --> 00:07:53.766
My daughter

120
00:07:54.026 --> 00:07:55.026
thinks I've gone a bit

121
00:07:55.156 --> 00:07:56.456
gaga, but she knows

122
00:07:56.636 --> 00:07:57.636
I'm right.

123
00:07:58.106 --> 00:08:00.196
The Nazis changed the wheels

124
00:08:00.326 --> 00:08:03.366
on that damned machine
every bloody day,


125
00:08:03.536 --> 00:08:07.106
that altered the code, and we
had to decipher it all over again.


126
00:08:07.756 --> 00:08:09.836
There were no computers
in those days,


127
00:08:10.276 --> 00:08:12.756
calculations were done by hand.

128
00:08:13.875 --> 00:08:15.275
You must have been very young.

129
00:08:15.445 --> 00:08:16.615
Time for me to go.

130
00:08:17.525 --> 00:08:19.095
Fancy a game of scrabble?

131
00:08:33.475 --> 00:08:35.775
Well, this is your study.

132
00:08:36.215 --> 00:08:38.075
I trust you'll be comfortable.

133
00:08:38.255 --> 00:08:39.335
It's perfect.

134
00:08:39.515 --> 00:08:42.075
You should also be thinking
of a supervisor


135
00:08:42.255 --> 00:08:43.295
for your thesis.

136
00:08:43.465 --> 00:08:46.505
I've had one in mind
for a long time; Arthur seldom.


137
00:08:50.765 --> 00:08:51.855
Your parents?

138
00:08:52.025 --> 00:08:53.065
Yeah.

139
00:08:54.585 --> 00:08:56.975
Very American.
Is it close to the beach?


140
00:08:57.155 --> 00:09:01.065
Not at all.
It's the desert, Arizona.


141
00:09:01.285 --> 00:09:02.845
It actually happens to be my home.

142
00:09:03.845 --> 00:09:06.145
Really? Lovely.

143
00:09:07.055 --> 00:09:08.185
Anyway...

144
00:09:08.405 --> 00:09:09.795
All the studies are shared.

145
00:09:10.365 --> 00:09:12.485
Your colleague is
also an overseas student.


146
00:09:12.665 --> 00:09:14.315
I'm sure we'll get on fine.

147
00:09:14.835 --> 00:09:15.835
By the way,

148
00:09:15.965 --> 00:09:20.095
I think you'll find professor seldom
only works as a researcher now.


149
00:09:20.655 --> 00:09:23.655
I know, but the college told me that
he could supervise my doctorate.


150
00:09:23.785 --> 00:09:25.265
Who told you that?

151
00:09:25.655 --> 00:09:27.435
I've got a fax...

152
00:09:27.695 --> 00:09:28.695
Here.

153
00:09:31.175 --> 00:09:32.255
I see.

154
00:09:33.175 --> 00:09:36.165
I'm sorry to say Mrs. keeman

155
00:09:36.475 --> 00:09:38.475
was being rather over-optimistic.
Also,


156
00:09:38.645 --> 00:09:39.865
she no longer works here.

157
00:09:39.995 --> 00:09:42.335
But there must be some way,
perhaps if I speak to him...


158
00:09:42.685 --> 00:09:43.945
You're free to talk
to whoever you want,


159
00:09:44.075 --> 00:09:48.075
of course, but I must
warn you professor seldom


160
00:09:48.205 --> 00:09:51.115
is not one for
this sort of spontaneity.


161
00:09:51.245 --> 00:09:52.895
If you take my advice,

162
00:09:53.065 --> 00:09:56.115
I suggest you approach your studies
in a more realistic way.


163
00:09:56.245 --> 00:09:59.285
I'm sure you'll find some excellent
tutors among our teaching staff


164
00:09:59.545 --> 00:10:02.625
who will more than understand
the nature of your work.


165
00:10:23.304 --> 00:10:25.394
- Don't take it out on the wall.
- Walls?


166
00:10:26.004 --> 00:10:28.764
Don't talk to me about walls. That's
all you get in this fucking city.


167
00:10:30.434 --> 00:10:32.474
Sorry, just letting off
a little steam.


168
00:10:32.644 --> 00:10:35.514
Well, at least they come in
handy for doing your homework.


169
00:10:36.864 --> 00:10:39.814
These? I was just trying to save
myself 16 years of practice.


170
00:10:41.254 --> 00:10:43.224
See, I'm trying to calculate
where I need to run,


171
00:10:43.254 --> 00:10:44.464
depending on where
the ball bounces,


172
00:10:44.644 --> 00:10:46.294
and what height it makes contact

173
00:10:46.464 --> 00:10:47.464
with my racquet.

174
00:10:47.814 --> 00:10:49.894
Makes it easier. Here.

175
00:10:55.714 --> 00:10:57.284
See? It works.

176
00:10:58.414 --> 00:11:01.674
Yeah, and what would happen
if you played against a person?


177
00:11:03.804 --> 00:11:05.234
There would be more variables

178
00:11:05.404 --> 00:11:08.444
but it would still be possible
to work out the trajectory.


179
00:11:10.234 --> 00:11:11.314
Please.

180
00:11:48.634 --> 00:11:49.894
Give me time.

181
00:11:50.544 --> 00:11:52.724
I have to rethink my calculations.

182
00:11:54.594 --> 00:11:55.594
Okay.

183
00:12:08.404 --> 00:12:09.534
Thanks for the beating.

184
00:12:10.314 --> 00:12:11.704
Do you want to continue
letting off steam


185
00:12:11.884 --> 00:12:13.324
on your own
or do you prefer company?


186
00:12:15.274 --> 00:12:16.964
Wednesday, same time?

187
00:12:17.224 --> 00:12:20.913
Yes. Bring a proper squash racquet.
Makes life much easier.


188
00:12:22.043 --> 00:12:23.043
Okay.

189
00:12:33.903 --> 00:12:37.123
I see you're picking up
the local customs very quickly.


190
00:12:37.293 --> 00:12:38.643
I try my best.

191
00:12:38.813 --> 00:12:40.733
Maybe she can help you
with your doctoral thesis,


192
00:12:40.863 --> 00:12:43.123
since uncle Arthur
is out of the question.


193
00:12:43.383 --> 00:12:44.983
- Can nothing be done?
- No.


194
00:12:45.813 --> 00:12:48.453
And if you're suggesting my mother
have a word with him, forget it.


195
00:12:49.073 --> 00:12:50.373
I wasn't suggesting anything.

196
00:12:50.983 --> 00:12:54.063
Do you really expect me to believe
you chose this house by chance?


197
00:12:55.063 --> 00:12:57.063
No, not by chance, no.

198
00:12:57.453 --> 00:12:58.673
Nothing happens by chance.

199
00:12:58.843 --> 00:13:00.543
I wanted to meet
your mother, that's true,


200
00:13:00.763 --> 00:13:02.623
but I never planned to use her.

201
00:13:02.803 --> 00:13:04.493
There's no need to apologize.

202
00:13:05.323 --> 00:13:07.363
I like people who
go for what they want.


203
00:13:07.583 --> 00:13:08.973
I wish I was more like you.

204
00:13:09.493 --> 00:13:11.533
You're not missing much,
i assure you.


205
00:13:11.663 --> 00:13:12.963
Oh, really?

206
00:13:13.143 --> 00:13:15.573
You come here from another country,
all on your own,


207
00:13:15.703 --> 00:13:18.223
and no sooner do you get here
than you make friends with a girl.


208
00:13:18.613 --> 00:13:21.093
With two, I hope.
At least that's what I thought


209
00:13:21.263 --> 00:13:23.743
- until a moment ago.
- It's not just that.


210
00:13:24.223 --> 00:13:25.353
You're happy,

211
00:13:26.523 --> 00:13:28.363
you only have to look at
your face to see that.


212
00:13:28.523 --> 00:13:29.693
I try to be.

213
00:13:29.823 --> 00:13:30.993
How do you do it?

214
00:13:32.213 --> 00:13:33.303
It's easy.

215
00:13:33.473 --> 00:13:34.873
It's a case of going
with the flow.


216
00:13:34.903 --> 00:13:36.473
And what if it goes badly?

217
00:13:40.683 --> 00:13:42.593
I'd rather make mistakes
than do nothing.


218
00:13:42.943 --> 00:13:45.423
I'd rather mess up
than miss out completely.


219
00:13:46.293 --> 00:13:47.503
It works for me.

220
00:13:48.243 --> 00:13:49.503
You should try it.

221
00:14:01.623 --> 00:14:02.803
Just a minute!

222
00:14:06.753 --> 00:14:08.403
I thought you might
find this interesting.


223
00:14:08.533 --> 00:14:10.363
Seldom is giving a lecture
on his latest book


224
00:14:10.533 --> 00:14:12.363
at merton college on the 24th!

225
00:14:12.533 --> 00:14:14.053
There's your big chance!

226
00:14:16.223 --> 00:14:18.743
There is no way
of finding a single


227
00:14:18.923 --> 00:14:22.433
absolute truth, an irrefutable
argument that might help to answer


228
00:14:22.613 --> 00:14:24.562
the questions of mankind.

229
00:14:25.782 --> 00:14:28.732
Philosophy, therefore, is dead.

230
00:14:30.392 --> 00:14:33.382
Because "whereof we cannot speak,

231
00:14:35.342 --> 00:14:38.122
thereof we must be silent."

232
00:14:53.412 --> 00:14:56.582
Oh, it seems that
someone does wish to speak.


233
00:14:58.062 --> 00:15:00.842
It appears you are not
in agreement with wittgenstein.


234
00:15:01.492 --> 00:15:05.322
That means either you have found
a contradiction in the arguments


235
00:15:05.452 --> 00:15:09.312
of the tractatus, or you have an
absolute truth to share with us all.


236
00:15:09.492 --> 00:15:11.702
I believe in the number pi.

237
00:15:16.222 --> 00:15:18.742
I'm sorry,
i didn't understand you.


238
00:15:18.922 --> 00:15:20.522
What was it
you said you believed in?


239
00:15:20.702 --> 00:15:25.002
In the number pi, in the golden
section, the fibonacci series.


240
00:15:25.172 --> 00:15:27.782
The essence of nature
is mathematical.


241
00:15:28.172 --> 00:15:30.082
There is a hidden meaning
beneath reality.


242
00:15:30.432 --> 00:15:34.252
Things are organized following
a model, a scheme, a logical series.


243
00:15:35.252 --> 00:15:36.512
Even the tiny snowflake

244
00:15:36.692 --> 00:15:39.642
includes a numerical basis
in its structure. Therefore,


245
00:15:39.812 --> 00:15:43.292
if we manage to discover
the secret meaning of numbers,


246
00:15:43.462 --> 00:15:45.942
we will know
the secret meaning of reality.


247
00:15:54.062 --> 00:15:55.152
Impressive!

248
00:15:56.322 --> 00:15:57.842
Translating his words into

249
00:15:58.022 --> 00:15:59.192
the queen's English,

250
00:16:01.322 --> 00:16:02.812
we find ourselves
faced with a fresh,


251
00:16:02.842 --> 00:16:06.012
rousing defence of mathematics,
as if numbers


252
00:16:06.192 --> 00:16:08.662
were pre-existing ideas in reality.

253
00:16:09.102 --> 00:16:11.402
Anyway, this is nothing new.

254
00:16:11.882 --> 00:16:14.832
Since man is incapable
of reconciling mind and matter,


255
00:16:15.012 --> 00:16:18.312
he tends to confer
some sort of entity on ideas,


256
00:16:18.482 --> 00:16:21.782
because he cannot bear the notion
that the purely abstract


257
00:16:21.962 --> 00:16:24.562
only exists in our brain.

258
00:16:28.001 --> 00:16:31.861
The beauty and Harmony
of a snowflake.


259
00:16:35.511 --> 00:16:36.691
How sweet!

260
00:16:36.951 --> 00:16:38.031
The butterfly

261
00:16:38.161 --> 00:16:39.731
that flutters its wings

262
00:16:39.901 --> 00:16:42.901
and causes a hurricane
on the other side of the world.


263
00:16:43.291 --> 00:16:46.031
We've been hearing about
that damn butterfly for decades,


264
00:16:46.161 --> 00:16:50.281
but who has been able
to predict a single hurricane?


265
00:16:56.371 --> 00:16:57.761
Nobody!

266
00:17:02.881 --> 00:17:04.101
Tell me something...

267
00:17:04.931 --> 00:17:08.751
Where is the beauty
and Harmony in cancer?


268
00:17:09.621 --> 00:17:11.531
What makes a cell

269
00:17:11.661 --> 00:17:14.181
suddenly decide to turn itself
into a killer metastasis


270
00:17:14.351 --> 00:17:17.831
and destroy the rest of
the cells in a healthy body?


271
00:17:19.661 --> 00:17:20.911
Does anyone know?

272
00:17:23.831 --> 00:17:24.871
No.

273
00:17:25.781 --> 00:17:28.131
Because we'd rather think
of snowflakes


274
00:17:28.301 --> 00:17:30.471
and butterflies than of pain,

275
00:17:31.211 --> 00:17:32.511
war

276
00:17:33.041 --> 00:17:34.821
or that book.

277
00:17:36.031 --> 00:17:37.291
Why?

278
00:17:37.951 --> 00:17:41.941
Because we need to think
that life has meaning,


279
00:17:42.461 --> 00:17:45.251
that everything
is governed by logic


280
00:17:45.421 --> 00:17:47.551
and not by mere chance.

281
00:17:48.551 --> 00:17:53.331
If I write 2 then 4 then 6,
then we feel good, because we know


282
00:17:53.501 --> 00:17:55.151
that next comes 8.

283
00:17:55.321 --> 00:17:56.761
We can foresee it,

284
00:17:57.321 --> 00:17:59.281
we are not in the hands

285
00:17:59.411 --> 00:18:00.671
of destiny.

286
00:18:02.231 --> 00:18:04.231
Unfortunately, however,

287
00:18:05.581 --> 00:18:08.791
this has nothing to do with truth.

288
00:18:10.231 --> 00:18:11.661
Don't you agree?

289
00:18:14.571 --> 00:18:15.571
This...

290
00:18:17.221 --> 00:18:18.611
Is only fear.

291
00:18:22.871 --> 00:18:24.131
Sad...

292
00:18:26.171 --> 00:18:27.481
But there you go.

293
00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:39.680
You must

294
00:18:39.860 --> 00:18:41.470
be Martin.

295
00:18:41.810 --> 00:18:43.510
At last we meet.

296
00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:46.380
But, I don't get it,
are you leaving?


297
00:18:46.550 --> 00:18:49.720
Yes, I'm leaving. It was a mistake.
It was all a big mistake.


298
00:18:51.460 --> 00:18:53.980
Things have not turned out
as you expected, I guess.


299
00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:56.630
No, they haven't.
You bet they haven't.


300
00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:59.060
I hope the hastiness
of your decision


301
00:18:59.230 --> 00:19:00.280
has nothing to do with

302
00:19:00.450 --> 00:19:01.450
professor seldom.

303
00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:04.450
News travels fast in Oxford.

304
00:19:04.580 --> 00:19:07.530
We are a little village of gossips.

305
00:19:08.580 --> 00:19:11.620
Anyway, I think you are wrong
about the great Sage.


306
00:19:12.440 --> 00:19:14.490
He was the best in his day, but...

307
00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:17.700
Now he just wants to sell books.
Like those assholes.


308
00:19:17.830 --> 00:19:19.180
A real seldom fan, eh?

309
00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:22.610
I have a framed photo
of him in my room.


310
00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:24.040
So he refused you too?

311
00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:28.780
I would rather jump out of
a window than ask him for help.


312
00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:32.080
I want nothing to do
with him or his books.


313
00:19:33.340 --> 00:19:35.210
I prefer the reader's digest.

314
00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:07.880
Taxi!

315
00:20:27.090 --> 00:20:27.780
Hello.

316
00:20:27.950 --> 00:20:30.910
Ah, we've got
the book you wanted!


317
00:20:34.079 --> 00:20:35.249
There.

318
00:22:19.309 --> 00:22:20.739
Fucking hell!

319
00:22:22.349 --> 00:22:23.609
What are you doing here?

320
00:22:24.129 --> 00:22:25.479
I live here.
What's your excuse?


321
00:22:26.909 --> 00:22:28.999
I came to visit an old friend.

322
00:22:29.909 --> 00:22:31.469
I'm sorry about before.

323
00:22:31.649 --> 00:22:33.529
No, don't apologize.
I talked a lot of rubbish.


324
00:22:33.559 --> 00:22:35.219
I tend to overact
when I have an audience.


325
00:22:35.249 --> 00:22:37.328
The truth is I just wanted
to attract your attention.


326
00:22:38.688 --> 00:22:40.028
You succeeded.

327
00:22:49.328 --> 00:22:50.678
September the 24th,

328
00:22:50.848 --> 00:22:53.498
1993. Inspector petersen,
Oxford police station.


329
00:22:53.678 --> 00:22:57.058
Investigating the murder
of Mrs. Julia eagleton.


330
00:22:57.758 --> 00:23:00.758
According to this report,
you and professor Arthur seldom


331
00:23:00.928 --> 00:23:03.798
discovered the body...
At the same time.


332
00:23:04.668 --> 00:23:07.008
Yes, we entered
the room together.


333
00:23:07.708 --> 00:23:10.268
Are you one of
professor seldom's students?


334
00:23:10.838 --> 00:23:11.838
No.

335
00:23:13.008 --> 00:23:15.138
- Do you work for him?
- No.


336
00:23:15.308 --> 00:23:17.658
Can you explain
why you were there together?


337
00:23:17.828 --> 00:23:18.828
No.

338
00:23:20.788 --> 00:23:22.478
To tell you the truth, I can't.

339
00:23:23.218 --> 00:23:24.778
I was also surprised
to see him there.


340
00:23:25.998 --> 00:23:28.388
So it was pure coincidence?

341
00:23:28.558 --> 00:23:30.998
Everything seems to point
to that being the case.


342
00:23:33.248 --> 00:23:37.728
And was this the first time
you'd seen professor seldom?


343
00:23:37.898 --> 00:23:41.548
Not exactly. I was at
a conference he gave this morning.


344
00:23:42.678 --> 00:23:44.248
I asked him a few questions.

345
00:23:44.768 --> 00:23:45.988
What sort of questions?

346
00:23:46.458 --> 00:23:47.588
Mathematical ones.

347
00:23:57.058 --> 00:23:59.058
It's not by chance that I went

348
00:23:59.238 --> 00:24:00.798
to Mrs. eagleton's house
this afternoon.


349
00:24:01.278 --> 00:24:03.578
I went there because
the murderer told me to.


350
00:24:03.748 --> 00:24:05.358
The murderer warned you?

351
00:24:06.008 --> 00:24:09.188
Yes, I received a note
during the conference.


352
00:24:09.358 --> 00:24:10.918
What did it say?

353
00:24:11.358 --> 00:24:12.658
Just one sentence:

354
00:24:13.358 --> 00:24:14.828
"The first of the series,"

355
00:24:15.308 --> 00:24:18.008
written in capital letters.
Underneath,


356
00:24:18.478 --> 00:24:20.398
Mrs. eagleton's address

357
00:24:20.918 --> 00:24:22.178
and the time.

358
00:24:22.518 --> 00:24:23.998
Can we see it?

359
00:24:24.958 --> 00:24:25.958
No.

360
00:24:26.608 --> 00:24:27.648
Why?

361
00:24:28.778 --> 00:24:29.998
I threw it away.

362
00:24:30.388 --> 00:24:32.598
You threw away
a vital piece of evidence?


363
00:24:35.948 --> 00:24:38.208
Yes, well, let me explain.

364
00:24:39.207 --> 00:24:41.027
After the conference,

365
00:24:41.207 --> 00:24:44.247
I signed a number of copies.
When I'd finished, I set off home.


366
00:24:45.247 --> 00:24:49.457
And that is when I realized
that the address on the note


367
00:24:49.627 --> 00:24:51.017
was familiar

368
00:24:51.677 --> 00:24:53.457
but honestly, I...

369
00:24:53.627 --> 00:24:57.927
It just never occurred to me that
anything like this could happen.


370
00:24:58.757 --> 00:25:01.017
Of course, when I got there,
it was too late.


371
00:25:14.787 --> 00:25:16.137
We should call the police.

372
00:25:16.347 --> 00:25:17.437
You're right.

373
00:25:18.997 --> 00:25:20.127
Call them.

374
00:25:22.997 --> 00:25:24.387
999.

375
00:25:24.567 --> 00:25:25.567
Hello,

376
00:25:25.737 --> 00:25:27.817
I'm calling to report a death.

377
00:25:28.907 --> 00:25:30.517
3 cunliffe close.

378
00:25:32.467 --> 00:25:33.687
It's an old woman.

379
00:25:34.947 --> 00:25:35.947
Thank you.

380
00:25:37.597 --> 00:25:38.947
What do you think happened?

381
00:25:39.377 --> 00:25:40.547
I don't know.

382
00:25:41.247 --> 00:25:43.637
We should wait outside.
We'd better not touch anything.


383
00:25:43.807 --> 00:25:45.377
I shouldn't have
even used this phone.


384
00:25:45.637 --> 00:25:48.897
Try to etch on your memory
everything you can see.


385
00:25:49.067 --> 00:25:51.197
This moment is crucial.

386
00:25:51.497 --> 00:25:53.587
She was playing scrabble
when it happened.


387
00:25:53.847 --> 00:25:55.017
Was she playing on her own?

388
00:25:55.497 --> 00:25:58.317
Yes, she has both
the letter racks on her side.


389
00:25:58.797 --> 00:26:00.407
You don't think she's been killed?

390
00:26:02.017 --> 00:26:03.797
I can't see any other alternative.

391
00:26:07.747 --> 00:26:10.097
Whoever did this obviously
intended to smother her


392
00:26:10.317 --> 00:26:11.527
with the cushion
while she was sleeping.


393
00:26:11.707 --> 00:26:13.397
She wakes up, puts up a struggle,

394
00:26:13.657 --> 00:26:16.217
he presses down harder,
using both hands perhaps,


395
00:26:16.397 --> 00:26:18.867
breaks her nose, hence the blood.

396
00:26:19.267 --> 00:26:20.827
Or it could have been a woman,

397
00:26:20.957 --> 00:26:23.437
using her knee
to add extra pressure.


398
00:26:24.437 --> 00:26:26.907
When the killer removes
the cushion, sees the blood,


399
00:26:27.037 --> 00:26:28.647
he drops it on the carpet
and doesn't even bother


400
00:26:28.817 --> 00:26:30.427
to put anything back in its place.

401
00:26:30.607 --> 00:26:32.037
Scared, probably.

402
00:26:34.557 --> 00:26:35.557
In the book

403
00:26:35.687 --> 00:26:38.897
that I based my conference on,
i unfortunately


404
00:26:39.247 --> 00:26:42.856
compare logical series
with serial murders.


405
00:26:43.326 --> 00:26:45.586
And since its publication
I've received


406
00:26:45.766 --> 00:26:47.376
dozens of totally absurd letters,

407
00:26:47.506 --> 00:26:49.196
which is why I attached
little importance to this one.


408
00:26:49.546 --> 00:26:51.626
And you're sure you destroyed it?

409
00:26:52.456 --> 00:26:55.536
Well, no, I threw it away
in the street.


410
00:26:55.716 --> 00:26:56.756
Where?

411
00:26:59.756 --> 00:27:01.576
Well, somewhere near
the sheldonian theatre.


412
00:27:01.706 --> 00:27:04.616
Scott, get on to it,
it might still be there.


413
00:27:04.746 --> 00:27:06.406
The road sweepers
will have passed through by now.


414
00:27:06.576 --> 00:27:09.746
It doesn't matter. We'll search
the dust carts, if necessary.


415
00:27:10.396 --> 00:27:14.266
Now is there anything else? Anything
else that caught your attention?


416
00:27:14.436 --> 00:27:17.046
Oh, uh, under the text

417
00:27:17.916 --> 00:27:19.916
there was a hand-drawn circle,

418
00:27:21.216 --> 00:27:22.826
a perfect circle,

419
00:27:24.306 --> 00:27:25.996
also in black.

420
00:27:27.556 --> 00:27:28.866
About...

421
00:27:31.556 --> 00:27:33.386
This size,

422
00:27:35.336 --> 00:27:36.506
approximately.

423
00:27:38.506 --> 00:27:39.686
A circle?

424
00:27:40.546 --> 00:27:41.726
Like a signature?

425
00:27:41.946 --> 00:27:44.116
Oh no, I'm almost convinced
it was a symbol,


426
00:27:44.286 --> 00:27:46.246
the first element
of a logical series.


427
00:27:47.506 --> 00:27:49.416
Well, excuse my ignorance,

428
00:27:49.586 --> 00:27:52.416
I must have been off school
the day they taught


429
00:27:52.546 --> 00:27:53.756
logical series.

430
00:27:54.496 --> 00:27:55.756
A logical series

431
00:27:55.936 --> 00:27:57.536
is a group of elements
that succeed one another,


432
00:27:57.756 --> 00:27:59.056
following a particular rule.

433
00:27:59.236 --> 00:28:00.366
Could be 1, 2, 3, 4...

434
00:28:00.536 --> 00:28:02.926
Or even numbers, 2, 4, 6, 8...

435
00:28:03.756 --> 00:28:06.316
Or of course it could be
the fibonacci series.


436
00:28:06.836 --> 00:28:08.226
Fibonacci?

437
00:28:08.396 --> 00:28:09.836
A 12th-century mathematician.

438
00:28:10.006 --> 00:28:14.526
Each element is the sum of the two
previous ones: 1, 1, 2, 3, 6,


439
00:28:14.696 --> 00:28:17.346
- 8, 13...
- Look, I still don't see


440
00:28:17.526 --> 00:28:20.476
the relationship between
the murder and these series.


441
00:28:20.656 --> 00:28:24.086
I'm sorry. In my book I sustain
the theory that the murder committed


442
00:28:24.306 --> 00:28:27.426
for intellectual reasons
does not exist in the real world.


443
00:28:28.476 --> 00:28:31.516
In general, the patterns
followed by a serial killer


444
00:28:31.686 --> 00:28:35.206
are crude, monotonous
and repetitive,


445
00:28:35.376 --> 00:28:38.686
cases that can be analyzed
psychologically, not logically.


446
00:28:38.856 --> 00:28:42.506
So you think the murderer is
killing to prove something to you?


447
00:28:43.416 --> 00:28:46.375
Yes, sadly, I believe
that to be the case.


448
00:28:46.845 --> 00:28:48.415
Murderer wants to prove me wrong.

449
00:28:48.545 --> 00:28:50.365
He wants to show that
he's more intelligent than I am


450
00:28:50.495 --> 00:28:51.935
and that he can beat me

451
00:28:52.105 --> 00:28:55.235
at my own game.
Somehow he knew of my friendship


452
00:28:55.405 --> 00:28:58.885
with Mrs. eagleton,
and decided to begin there.


453
00:28:59.055 --> 00:29:01.625
How about this circle?
How do you explain this?


454
00:29:01.885 --> 00:29:04.445
Oh, a circle's a good way
to start a logical series.


455
00:29:04.615 --> 00:29:06.185
There's no symbol
more indeterminate.


456
00:29:06.405 --> 00:29:07.925
Could mean almost anything.

457
00:29:08.095 --> 00:29:12.045
So you mean there's gonna be
another murder after this one?


458
00:29:12.395 --> 00:29:13.655
I'm afraid so.

459
00:29:15.745 --> 00:29:17.525
And if we don't
discover it in time,


460
00:29:17.875 --> 00:29:19.565
could be many more.

461
00:29:19.735 --> 00:29:21.385
Okay, we are going to change

462
00:29:21.565 --> 00:29:24.045
some notes please in part 12.

463
00:29:24.215 --> 00:29:26.825
We knew she was going
to die at any time,


464
00:29:27.775 --> 00:29:29.255
but never like this.

465
00:29:29.645 --> 00:29:32.645
The doctors gave her 6 months
to live, 6 years ago.


466
00:29:33.035 --> 00:29:36.245
Thanks to Beth's nursing
she had an extra lease of life,


467
00:29:36.725 --> 00:29:38.205
like a blessing from heaven.

468
00:29:39.295 --> 00:29:41.245
Maybe that's why
the murderer chose her.


469
00:29:42.375 --> 00:29:43.635
How do you mean?

470
00:29:43.935 --> 00:29:46.415
If he is trying to demonstrate
something purely intellectual,


471
00:29:46.585 --> 00:29:49.025
maybe the deaths in themselves
don't interest him.


472
00:29:49.235 --> 00:29:52.155
Maybe his aim is to inflict
as little harm as possible.


473
00:29:52.325 --> 00:29:54.455
He chose someone
that should have died.


474
00:29:54.585 --> 00:29:56.925
He probably knew Mrs. eagleton
was receiving treatment...


475
00:29:57.105 --> 00:29:59.405
She went every week
to st Joseph's hospital.


476
00:29:59.575 --> 00:30:03.015
He could have found out about her
illness there, and that made her


477
00:30:03.185 --> 00:30:04.965
the perfect victim for him.

478
00:30:05.315 --> 00:30:06.405
Go on.

479
00:30:07.615 --> 00:30:09.355
If he hadn't broken her nose,

480
00:30:09.525 --> 00:30:11.705
it would have looked
like death by natural causes.


481
00:30:11.965 --> 00:30:14.145
In that case, only you
would have known what happened.


482
00:30:14.175 --> 00:30:15.875
The police would never
have been involved.


483
00:30:16.085 --> 00:30:18.135
It would have been
a private challenge.


484
00:30:18.345 --> 00:30:20.175
A murder that almost isn't a murder.

485
00:30:20.345 --> 00:30:21.995
That makes sense.

486
00:30:23.255 --> 00:30:24.865
What do you think
he would do next?


487
00:30:25.565 --> 00:30:27.775
I suppose he'll try
to be more careful.


488
00:30:28.255 --> 00:30:31.165
He'll commit another murder
that almost isn't a murder.


489
00:30:32.465 --> 00:30:35.205
An imperceptible murder...

490
00:30:40.205 --> 00:30:41.375
Excuse me.

491
00:30:46.415 --> 00:30:48.974
Excuse me, officers,
but I need to speak


492
00:30:49.154 --> 00:30:50.994
to miss eagleton first,
to break the bad news,


493
00:30:51.024 --> 00:30:53.284
to her, if that's all right.
Thank you.


494
00:31:00.014 --> 00:31:01.404
You have a c,

495
00:31:01.574 --> 00:31:04.404
b flat, and c sharp.

496
00:31:04.574 --> 00:31:06.354
Excuse me, please,
i can talk to him?


497
00:31:06.534 --> 00:31:09.314
Yes, so

498
00:31:09.484 --> 00:31:10.834
you have a c, b flat,

499
00:31:11.004 --> 00:31:12.394
and c sharp.

500
00:31:14.004 --> 00:31:16.954
Oh, no, no, no. You have a b,
a c sharp, and c natural...


501
00:31:18.084 --> 00:31:19.134
Oh, okay,

502
00:31:19.734 --> 00:31:21.344
let's do a break, please.

503
00:31:56.274 --> 00:31:58.684
The police told me that you
were the one who found the body.


504
00:31:58.714 --> 00:32:00.404
Forgive me, Beth.
I'm really sorry.


505
00:32:00.574 --> 00:32:02.654
They asked me to try
and remember every detail and...


506
00:32:02.754 --> 00:32:05.744
It's no problem.
I understand.


507
00:32:08.964 --> 00:32:11.404
It must have been difficult
for you to go through all of this.


508
00:32:12.044 --> 00:32:14.044
Two hours of interrogation.

509
00:32:14.394 --> 00:32:17.174
It's logical, though, bearing
in mind I'm the chief suspect.


