01:26:47.617 --> 01:26:48.357
The tetraktys...

1499
01:26:48.487 --> 01:26:51.007
Exactly. The message
indicates a particular place.


1500
01:26:51.177 --> 01:26:52.397
He told us to send ambulances there.

1501
01:26:52.527 --> 01:26:53.537
A road?

1502
01:26:53.567 --> 01:26:55.607
The a421. Just past
the black cat roundabout.


1503
01:26:55.737 --> 01:26:57.257
That's the road to Cambridge.

1504
01:26:58.257 --> 01:26:59.617
There's a flyover
on the main road.


1505
01:26:59.647 --> 01:27:01.387
Petersen's already on his way.

1506
01:27:01.567 --> 01:27:03.737
He'll try to stop the bus
before it reaches that spot.


1507
01:27:09.117 --> 01:27:10.687
Have you located the bus yet?

1508
01:27:10.857 --> 01:27:12.507
It's three miles from where

1509
01:27:12.687 --> 01:27:14.247
you are, sir.
You'll be meeting up


1510
01:27:14.417 --> 01:27:15.547
in under a minute.

1511
01:27:17.547 --> 01:27:18.807
Petersen here, to all units.

1512
01:27:18.987 --> 01:27:21.117
The murderer may be travelling

1513
01:27:21.287 --> 01:27:24.457
with them, so keep your heads
down until I give the word.


1514
01:27:48.697 --> 01:27:50.487
Where are they?
I can't see them.


1515
01:27:52.477 --> 01:27:54.087
- Right in front of you, sir.
- Got it!


1516
01:27:55.127 --> 01:27:55.917
Now!

1517
01:27:56.087 --> 01:27:57.087
Now!

1518
01:28:05.947 --> 01:28:07.037
Jesus!

1519
01:28:23.066 --> 01:28:25.676
Turn off the engine!
Put your hands on the wheel!


1520
01:28:28.366 --> 01:28:29.366
We made it in time.

1521
01:28:30.066 --> 01:28:31.366
They've stopped the bus.

1522
01:28:31.536 --> 01:28:33.146
Seldom and the other
mathematicians are safe.


1523
01:28:33.276 --> 01:28:36.536
Seldom? What have you done?
You've got the wrong bus!


1524
01:29:02.296 --> 01:29:03.316
Hello?

1525
01:29:03.346 --> 01:29:06.386
Seldom, you have to speak with
petersen, there's another bus!


1526
01:29:06.556 --> 01:29:07.646
What are you talking about?

1527
01:29:07.816 --> 01:29:09.126
It's the girl's father!

1528
01:29:09.296 --> 01:29:10.516
What girl?

1529
01:29:18.026 --> 01:29:19.116
Martin?

1530
01:29:19.986 --> 01:29:21.196
Martin, can you hear me?

1531
01:29:21.376 --> 01:29:24.236
The girl in the hospital,
she needs a transplant.


1532
01:29:24.416 --> 01:29:26.846
He wants to kill
the kids to save her!


1533
01:29:43.136 --> 01:29:44.136
Sir?

1534
01:29:44.316 --> 01:29:47.046
Excuse me, sir.
Sir, this way, please.


1535
01:29:47.706 --> 01:29:49.616
- That bus has to be stopped!
- Calm down, sir.


1536
01:29:49.786 --> 01:29:51.946
They're going to be killed!
I have to talk to petersen!


1537
01:29:52.746 --> 01:29:55.606
Sir, one of the professors
insists on speaking to you.


1538
01:29:55.736 --> 01:29:57.296
He's completely
lost control of himself.


1539
01:30:14.896 --> 01:30:16.596
Oh what the hell?

1540
01:30:31.535 --> 01:30:34.715
You.
Did you know about this?


1541
01:30:35.275 --> 01:30:37.835
Did you fucking know about this?

1542
01:30:38.015 --> 01:30:39.575
You and your fucking equations!

1543
01:30:51.305 --> 01:30:52.785
I don't know anything.

1544
01:30:58.735 --> 01:30:59.905
Nothing.

1545
01:31:49.705 --> 01:31:52.825
Five of the victims
are possible donors.


1546
01:31:54.085 --> 01:31:56.395
Five organs offer a fair chance.

1547
01:31:56.825 --> 01:31:58.385
They're rushing them off
to st Joseph's.


1548
01:31:58.565 --> 01:32:00.085
That's why he sent the ambulances.

1549
01:32:00.255 --> 01:32:01.775
That's right.

1550
01:32:02.955 --> 01:32:04.775
The petrol tank
was down to a minimum.


1551
01:32:04.945 --> 01:32:06.515
He wanted to cause
as little harm as possible,


1552
01:32:06.685 --> 01:32:09.595
only this time
it wasn't exactly imperceptible.


1553
01:32:10.685 --> 01:32:12.375
Why all these?
Why all the symbols?


1554
01:32:12.815 --> 01:32:14.985
He didn't plan
to die in the accident.


1555
01:32:15.115 --> 01:32:18.155
His idea was to jump in time
to avoid being a suspect.


1556
01:32:18.335 --> 01:32:19.335
How do you know?

1557
01:32:20.675 --> 01:32:23.545
When the bus crashed,
the doors were already open.


1558
01:32:24.894 --> 01:32:26.364
And what about the other deaths?

1559
01:32:27.064 --> 01:32:28.934
Well, if only the children
had been killed,


1560
01:32:29.104 --> 01:32:30.714
he would have been
the prime suspect.


1561
01:32:30.884 --> 01:32:32.664
Making us believe
in a serial killer


1562
01:32:32.844 --> 01:32:34.274
took the spotlight off him.

1563
01:32:34.404 --> 01:32:37.404
Only he miscalculated
and didn't get out in time.


1564
01:32:38.314 --> 01:32:40.884
So, he didn't really want
to kill the other people,


1565
01:32:41.274 --> 01:32:44.004
- he just needed an alibi?
- Exactly.


1566
01:32:44.874 --> 01:32:47.484
Shame we didn't work it out sooner.

1567
01:32:47.834 --> 01:32:48.874
So much

1568
01:32:49.044 --> 01:32:50.174
for logic.

1569
01:33:37.494 --> 01:33:39.884
You were just a pawn in his game.

1570
01:33:41.144 --> 01:33:43.354
You have nothing
to feel guilty about.


1571
01:33:52.784 --> 01:33:55.304
You don't know what you're saying.

1572
01:34:17.244 --> 01:34:19.204
You don't need to get on a plane.

1573
01:34:20.244 --> 01:34:21.324
Sorry?

1574
01:34:21.504 --> 01:34:24.934
I said, you don't need to get on
a plane. You're already miles away.


1575
01:34:25.544 --> 01:34:26.674
I was just thinking...

1576
01:34:26.844 --> 01:34:27.844
Really?

1577
01:34:32.323 --> 01:34:34.193
Ok.
From now on,


1578
01:34:34.363 --> 01:34:36.103
we are just two tourists

1579
01:34:36.273 --> 01:34:39.533
in an airport with the heaviest
rucksack I've ever seen.


1580
01:34:41.183 --> 01:34:42.573
What did you pack in here anyway?

1581
01:34:42.793 --> 01:34:45.573
Oh, you know, just the essentials.
A double bed, a cooker,


1582
01:34:45.743 --> 01:34:47.173
for making spaghetti

1583
01:34:47.353 --> 01:34:49.003
- and a couple of other things.
- Well, I hope


1584
01:34:49.173 --> 01:34:50.833
you didn't pack a single
one of your mystery novels.


1585
01:34:51.003 --> 01:34:51.693
Of course not!

1586
01:34:51.873 --> 01:34:54.743
No mystery novels,
no symbols, no Oxford.


1587
01:34:54.913 --> 01:34:56.653
We had a deal, remember?

1588
01:34:56.913 --> 01:34:58.433
You gonna be able to live like this?

1589
01:34:59.473 --> 01:35:00.603
Yes.

1590
01:35:00.773 --> 01:35:01.863
Just you and me.

1591
01:35:07.463 --> 01:35:08.463
Come on.

1592
01:35:17.243 --> 01:35:18.373
Thank you.

1593
01:35:27.413 --> 01:35:29.153
Can I have your
boarding pass, please?


1594
01:35:29.363 --> 01:35:30.583
He didn't know!

1595
01:35:30.933 --> 01:35:31.933
Martin?

1596
01:35:33.273 --> 01:35:34.353
That old fucker tricked me!

1597
01:35:35.973 --> 01:35:37.573
He didn't know
what the third symbol was!


1598
01:35:46.613 --> 01:35:47.743
My god!

1599
01:35:48.443 --> 01:35:50.093
You've got the pictures with you?

1600
01:35:51.523 --> 01:35:52.873
What is this?

1601
01:35:54.263 --> 01:35:55.263
"Kreis".

1602
01:35:58.693 --> 01:36:00.043
What is that?

1603
01:36:09.643 --> 01:36:12.643
She spent 3 years
deciphering German codes.


1604
01:36:12.813 --> 01:36:13.763
Excuse me, sir,
you can't do that here.


1605
01:36:13.943 --> 01:36:14.943
Of course!

1606
01:36:15.073 --> 01:36:17.333
Kreis is German for circle.

1607
01:36:17.763 --> 01:36:19.243
He came up with it on the spot!

1608
01:36:58.562 --> 01:36:59.912
Have you been here before?

1609
01:37:02.032 --> 01:37:03.562
I never had a chance.

1610
01:37:05.422 --> 01:37:08.812
It would be a pity to leave the
country without seeing this place.


1611
01:37:10.642 --> 01:37:11.812
This is the largest

1612
01:37:11.982 --> 01:37:14.202
collection of fakes in the world.

1613
01:37:14.462 --> 01:37:16.152
Not even Michelangelo

1614
01:37:16.332 --> 01:37:18.682
can distinguish
this David from his original.


1615
01:37:20.242 --> 01:37:23.542
Trajan's column
we believe to be in Rome,


1616
01:37:24.542 --> 01:37:29.062
but we are sure
that this is a common


1617
01:37:29.282 --> 01:37:31.322
plaster copy.

1618
01:37:32.402 --> 01:37:34.052
I feel at ease here.

1619
01:37:34.662 --> 01:37:36.792
No one tries to deceive me.

1620
01:37:37.442 --> 01:37:39.312
In effect, Martin,
this is the place


1621
01:37:39.492 --> 01:37:42.482
that contains the most truth
in the entire planet.


1622
01:37:43.662 --> 01:37:46.832
We have an absolute truth:

1623
01:37:48.002 --> 01:37:50.352
Everything is fake.

1624
01:37:51.612 --> 01:37:53.432
Outside of these walls

1625
01:37:53.612 --> 01:37:55.652
nobody is sure of anything.

1626
01:37:58.602 --> 01:38:02.082
You took a big risk in giving me
a blank piece of paper.


1627
01:38:05.732 --> 01:38:09.032
That was important.
I had to convince you that I knew


1628
01:38:09.202 --> 01:38:12.112
what the sign was when, at
that moment, I wasn't at all sure.


1629
01:38:12.682 --> 01:38:14.722
I knew you wouldn't
let me down, Martin.


1630
01:38:14.892 --> 01:38:17.412
Your pride wouldn't let you open
this piece of paper


1631
01:38:17.592 --> 01:38:19.042
until you had
a solution of your own,


1632
01:38:19.072 --> 01:38:22.892
and that, if I might say,
was going to take some time.


1633
01:38:23.542 --> 01:38:25.322
There was no serial killer.

1634
01:38:26.062 --> 01:38:28.802
It was an invention,
just like petersen said.


1635
01:38:29.322 --> 01:38:31.532
But it wasn't
the bus driver's invention.


1636
01:38:31.882 --> 01:38:32.932
It was yours.

1637
01:38:33.582 --> 01:38:36.841
You invented a series of killings
to hide the only real crime:


1638
01:38:37.441 --> 01:38:40.221
The death of Mrs. eagleton.
Beth killed her,


1639
01:38:40.401 --> 01:38:42.741
just as the police had suspected
from the very beginning.


1640
01:38:48.091 --> 01:38:50.301
Beth hated her life.
She couldn't put up


1641
01:38:50.481 --> 01:38:52.351
with that woman any more
so she killed her.


1642
01:38:52.521 --> 01:38:54.521
That's when she sent you a note

1643
01:38:54.821 --> 01:38:56.211
asking for help.

1644
01:38:56.521 --> 01:38:58.471
I couldn't look her in the face.

1645
01:39:00.041 --> 01:39:02.361
It was my fault that her father
was killed in that accident


1646
01:39:02.471 --> 01:39:04.601
30 years ago.

1647
01:39:05.681 --> 01:39:07.291
I couldn't let her down again.

1648
01:39:07.471 --> 01:39:09.161
We both met at the door.

1649
01:39:09.511 --> 01:39:11.071
You'd come to get rid
of the evidence,


1650
01:39:11.201 --> 01:39:14.071
but I was there, in the way,
and that spoiled everything.


1651
01:39:15.371 --> 01:39:17.151
You had to come up with
a new plan, in front of me,


1652
01:39:17.281 --> 01:39:20.461
just moments before the police
arrived. You read the word


1653
01:39:20.631 --> 01:39:22.281
"circle" in German
on the scrabble rack,


1654
01:39:22.411 --> 01:39:23.491
and that gave you the idea.

1655
01:39:25.061 --> 01:39:26.501
A series with
infinite possibilities.


1656
01:39:26.671 --> 01:39:28.361
But you needed a second death

1657
01:39:28.541 --> 01:39:30.931
to convince the police
that the murderer was not Beth.


1658
01:39:31.101 --> 01:39:32.971
And unwittingly, I helped you.

1659
01:39:34.921 --> 01:39:38.271
I gave you the idea of how
to do it, without even realising.


1660
01:39:38.571 --> 01:39:39.831
An imperceptible murder.

1661
01:39:40.221 --> 01:39:41.481
A murderer who only kills

1662
01:39:41.621 --> 01:39:42.621
someone who is at

1663
01:39:42.791 --> 01:39:44.001
death's door. You only had

1664
01:39:44.181 --> 01:39:46.651
to wait for the occasion
and prick the body with a syringe.


1665
01:39:47.091 --> 01:39:49.781
That's when you sent
the second message. The fish.


1666
01:39:50.611 --> 01:39:53.091
You still didn't know
where all this was going to lead.


1667
01:39:53.261 --> 01:39:56.301
The possibilities of continuing
the series were still infinite.


1668
01:39:56.471 --> 01:39:58.651
You had to wait for
another occasion to arise.


1669
01:39:58.821 --> 01:40:00.911
And that could take weeks, months.

1670
01:40:01.041 --> 01:40:02.301
There was no hurry.

1671
01:40:02.641 --> 01:40:05.251
You probably had a different plan
for the third death,


1672
01:40:05.471 --> 01:40:08.601
but that triangle player suddenly
appeared like a gift from the gods,


1673
01:40:09.551 --> 01:40:12.511
- and you had your solution.
- At first I rejected it.


1674
01:40:12.681 --> 01:40:13.941
Too many people, too operatic.

1675
01:40:15.161 --> 01:40:15.891
Don't lie.

1676
01:40:16.071 --> 01:40:17.071
You couldn't waste

1677
01:40:17.201 --> 01:40:18.411
a chance like that.

1678
01:40:18.851 --> 01:40:22.151
What's more, there was a triangle.
It all took on meaning!


1679
01:40:23.111 --> 01:40:25.891
Beautiful... it was as if
the damned pythagoreans


1680
01:40:26.061 --> 01:40:27.541
were on your side.

1681
01:40:27.801 --> 01:40:30.541
It was perfect,
but what's more important,


1682
01:40:30.711 --> 01:40:32.491
it was totally inoffensive.

1683
01:40:32.841 --> 01:40:34.621
Until the madman appeared.

1684
01:40:35.451 --> 01:40:38.790
Any one of our acts can have
unexpected consequences.


1685
01:40:38.960 --> 01:40:40.140
That's what you most feared.

1686
01:40:41.440 --> 01:40:42.700
Who was to know that poor devil

1687
01:40:42.880 --> 01:40:44.960
was going to read
the article in the paper?


1688
01:40:45.130 --> 01:40:47.920
He was looking for a solution
to his daughter's problem,


1689
01:40:48.180 --> 01:40:51.000
while every day he drove to school
those healthy children


1690
01:40:51.170 --> 01:40:53.480
with perfect lungs
but damaged brains.


1691
01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:56.130
Why did they deserve to live
and not his daughter?


1692
01:40:56.650 --> 01:41:00.600
Mathematicians are not the only ones
familiar with the greeks, professor.


1693
01:41:00.820 --> 01:41:03.990
You gave him his solution
when you published the series.


1694
01:41:04.160 --> 01:41:06.380
He also wanted to hide his crime.

1695
01:41:06.680 --> 01:41:08.990
He only had to make
a phone call, and he did.


1696
01:41:20.890 --> 01:41:22.110
So...

1697
01:41:23.850 --> 01:41:25.320
You think I'm the killer.

1698
01:41:26.280 --> 01:41:27.360
No.

1699
01:41:27.630 --> 01:41:29.360
You haven't killed anyone,

1700
01:41:29.880 --> 01:41:33.620
but you're guilty of provoking the
deaths of those innocent children.


1701
01:41:34.360 --> 01:41:36.230
You're guilty of arrogance,

1702
01:41:36.530 --> 01:41:39.310
of using us all like
pieces on a board game.


1703
01:41:40.400 --> 01:41:42.310
Who the hell do you think you are?

1704
01:41:45.310 --> 01:41:49.260
I hope my failure has, at least,
served to teach you something.


1705
01:41:51.220 --> 01:41:53.040
Yes, one thing.

1706
01:41:53.820 --> 01:41:55.870
One very painful thing.

1707
01:41:56.820 --> 01:41:58.690
Numbers also lie.

1708
01:41:59.120 --> 01:42:02.120
The truth is not mathematical,
as I once believed.


1709
01:42:02.560 --> 01:42:05.080
It's absurd, confused, random,

1710
01:42:05.250 --> 01:42:07.770
disorderly, and deeply unpleasant.

1711
01:42:08.600 --> 01:42:12.160
I'm glad that finally we can agree
on something, Martin, my friend.


1712
01:42:13.110 --> 01:42:15.330
Just one thing has escaped you.

1713
01:42:19.980 --> 01:42:21.590
The real culprit.

1714
01:42:23.280 --> 01:42:26.280
The one who triggered off
this whole string of crimes.


1715
01:42:26.410 --> 01:42:27.800
Who?

1716
01:42:27.970 --> 01:42:29.150
You, Martin.

1717
01:42:30.360 --> 01:42:31.540
Don't make me laugh.

1718
01:42:31.710 --> 01:42:34.100
If you don't believe me,
then speak to Beth.


1719
01:42:34.970 --> 01:42:36.580
She was in love with you,

1720
01:42:37.490 --> 01:42:39.100
or weren't you aware of that?

1721
01:42:40.490 --> 01:42:43.179
She remembered
your words exactly.


1722
01:42:44.829 --> 01:42:46.529
"You should try it."

1723
01:42:47.089 --> 01:42:50.389
"You should try it,"
pounded time and again


1724
01:42:50.569 --> 01:42:52.519
inside her head, like a hammer.

1725
01:42:53.609 --> 01:42:55.869
"You should be free, like me."

1726
01:42:58.299 --> 01:43:00.249
That's what she understood,

1727
01:43:01.689 --> 01:43:03.299
and that's what she did.

1728
01:43:04.729 --> 01:43:07.679
Put an end to what
prevented her from being free...


1729
01:43:11.159 --> 01:43:12.899
Her own mother.

1730
01:43:14.239 --> 01:43:15.289
The butterfly

1731
01:43:16.759 --> 01:43:19.329
that flutters its wings
and causes a hurricane


1732
01:43:19.499 --> 01:43:21.459
on the other side of the world.

1733
01:43:23.979 --> 01:43:25.709
Sound familiar?

1734
01:43:28.629 --> 01:43:30.999
Are you that butterfly, Martin?